56. Merge Intervals
Problem Statement

Given an array of intervals where intervals[i] = [starti, endi], merge all overlapping intervals and return the non-overlapping intervals.

Example
Input
[[1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
Output
[[1,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
Explanation
[1,3] and [2,6] overlap

So they merge into:

[1,6]
Approach
Key Observation

Two intervals overlap if:

currentStart <= previousEnd

Example:

[1,3] and [2,6]

Since:

2 <= 3

they overlap.

Main Idea
Sort intervals based on starting time.
Store first interval in result.
Traverse remaining intervals.
If overlap exists → merge.
Else → add new interval.
Why Sorting is Necessary

Before sorting:

[[8,10],[1,3],[2,6]]

After sorting:

[[1,3],[2,6],[8,10]]

Now overlapping intervals become adjacent.

Java Code
class Solution {

    public int[][] merge(int[][] intervals) {

        // Sort intervals based on starting value
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (a, b) -> a[0] - b[0]);

        // Store merged intervals
        List<int[]> result = new ArrayList<>();

        // Add first interval
        result.add(intervals[0]);

        // Traverse remaining intervals
        for (int i = 1; i < intervals.length; i++) {

            // Last merged interval
            int[] last = result.get(result.size() - 1);

            // Check overlap
            if (intervals[i][0] <= last[1]) {

                // Merge intervals
                last[1] = Math.max(last[1], intervals[i][1]);

            } else {

                // No overlap
                result.add(intervals[i]);
            }
        }

        // Convert list to array
        return result.toArray(new int[result.size()][]);
    }
}
Code Explanation
Step 1 — Sorting
Arrays.sort(intervals, (a, b) -> a[0] - b[0]);

Sort intervals according to starting value.

Example:

[1,3] comes before [2,6]

because:

1 < 2
Lambda Function
(a, b) -> a[0] - b[0]

means:

compare intervals using first element

Comparator Rules:

negative → a comes before b
positive → a comes after b
zero     → equal
Step 2 — Result List
List<int[]> result = new ArrayList<>();

Used to store merged intervals dynamically.

Step 3 — Add First Interval
result.add(intervals[0]);

Initialize result with first interval.

Step 4 — Traverse Remaining Intervals
for (int i = 1; i < intervals.length; i++)

Start from index 1 because first interval already added.

Step 5 — Get Last Merged Interval
int[] last = result.get(result.size() - 1);

Gets the most recently merged interval.

Step 6 — Overlap Check
if (intervals[i][0] <= last[1])

Condition:

currentStart <= previousEnd

If true → intervals overlap.

Step 7 — Merge Intervals
last[1] = Math.max(last[1], intervals[i][1]);

Update ending value with maximum end.

Example:

[1,3] and [2,6]

becomes:

[1,6]
Step 8 — No Overlap
result.add(intervals[i]);

If intervals do not overlap, add new interval separately.

Step 9 — Convert List to Array
return result.toArray(new int[result.size()][]);

Converts:

List<int[]>

into:

int[][]

because function return type is 2D array.

Dry Run
Input
[[1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
Initially
result = [[1,3]]
Compare [2,6]
2 <= 3

Overlap exists.

Merge:

[[1,6]]
Compare [8,10]
8 <= 6

No overlap.

Add separately:

[[1,6],[8,10]]
Compare [15,18]
15 <= 10

No overlap.

Final:

[[1,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
Time Complexity
Sorting
O(n log n)
Traversal
O(n)
Total
O(n log n)
Space Complexity
O(n)

for storing merged intervals.

Key Takeaway

The entire problem depends on one condition:

currentStart <= previousEnd
TRUE → Merge intervals
FALSE → Add new interval separately
